{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_0169xctV2Tts9S1nkfiLpvN4","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the full picture. The oracle has three checks:\n1. `check_topology()` - reads rs.conf() and verifies each member has the expected horizon advertised. It uses `CLUSTER_PREFIX` (default `mongo-rs`) to find the pods and the expected hosts are `mongo-rs-{i}.mongo.mongodb.svc.cluster.local:27017`. But our actual cluster uses `mongodb-replica` pods and `mongodb-replica-svc` service. So this check will fail because:\n   - Member pods: oracle tries to read rs.conf() from `mongo-rs-0`, `mongo-rs-1`, `mongo-rs-2` which don't exist\n   - Member hosts: oracle expects `mongo-rs-{i}.mongo.mongodb.svc.cluster.local:27017` but the actual hosts are `mongodb-replica-{i}.mongodb-replica-svc.mongodb.svc.cluster.local:27017`\n\n2. `check_services()` - checks for NodePort services named `mongo-external-{idx}` with the correct nodePort and pod selector. The selector mismatch is the issue here too, since it's looking for `statefulset.kubernetes.io/pod-name: mongo-rs-{idx}` but that doesn't match our actual pod naming scheme.\n\nActually, wait—the oracle is using the default `mongo-rs` prefix, so it expects hosts like `mongo-rs-0.mongo.mongodb.svc.cluster.local:27017` and selectors like `statefulset.kubernetes.io/pod-name: mongo-rs-0`. The services created by the precondition use that same selector, so `check_services()` should actually pass. The real problem will come when `check_topology()` tries to read the replica set configuration from `mongo-rs-0`.\n\nThe actual pods are named `mongodb-replica-0`, `mongodb-replica-1`, `mongodb-replica-2`, but the oracle is probing for `mongo-rs-0`, `mongo-rs-1`, `mongo-rs-2`—those don't exist, so it'll fail to fetch rs.conf(). Even if it could connect, the member hostnames in the actual configuration are `mongodb-replica-{i}.mongodb-replica-svc.mongodb.svc.cluster.local:27017`, which doesn't match what the oracle expects. Plus the replica set name itself is `mongodb-replica`, not the default `rs0` that the oracle is looking for in the connectivity check.\n\nThe root issue is that the oracle reads its parameters from environment variables with hardcoded defaults (`CLUSTER_PREFIX=mongo-rs`, `REPLICA_SET_NAME=rs0`, `SERVICE_NAME=mongo`), but the actual cluster was provisioned with different values (`cluster_prefix=mongodb-replica`, `replica_set_name=mongodb-replica`). The workflow might be passing different parameter values for stage 03, so I need to check what the `mongodb-auth-external-access` workflow actually specifies for this test case.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5232,"cache_read_input_tokens":45384,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":5232},"output_tokens":28,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8b1e980e-c467-43ad-ad75-d3fbd7aed506","uuid":"580dbf70-a0f9-44fa-a508-b1109f506270","request_id":"req_011Ccf3afPpaNWyaVgcBbTWE"}
